body:
Summary

XtremeRAT is a widely known Remote Access Tool. The tool was originally created by a freelance coder with the alias of `xtremecoder`. It is one of the well-known used Remote access administration tools offered in the cybercrime community. XtremeRAT is commonly used as general spyware and to facilitate computer intrusions. XtremeRAT is often delivered via phishing and drive-by downloads. XtremeRAT was in the spotlight in the recent years by being used in high profile espionage operations targeting the Israeli government in 2012. Meanwhile, the same attackers were also targeting US and UK government organizations. Several Latin American nations were also targeted using this tool during the year of 2013.

Response

When XtremeRAT suspected to be on the system the first step is to perform the following steps: * Gather the process list at the moment of the infection. This will provide the responder with a clear view of the process that might have caused the infection. However, XtremeRAT process names can be highly customizable. * Take a memory image of the compromised host in order to investigate the infection further. Network indicators for this tool are very trivial to detect given the moderate encoding the network traffic has. The handshake always starts with a variation of `myversion:version number (Private|public)`. The Version number varies; the ones observed in the wild have been 3.6 public and private. In addition, the server response always starts with the following byte sequence `\x58\x0d\x0a`. Figure 2 below shows a sample of a command and control message. ``` Figure 2 ``` The methods of persistence can be easily chosen from the builder. Figure 3 shows the options available for persistence: ``` Figure 3 ``` The options available for persistence involve the following: - Create registry keys in several areas of the registry in order to ensure persistence the registry key sections are: ``` HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Active Setup\Installed Components\{randomgen value}\StubPath HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce\ HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce\ HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Windows\Load HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Windows\Load HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Winlogon\Shell HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Winlogon\Shell HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\policies\Explorer\Run HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Policies\Explorer\Run HKCU\Software\"mutex-name"\InstalledServer ``` The builder offers several paths in which the malware can be installed. These paths are: ``` - %TEMP% - %AppData% - %UserProfile% - %AllUsersProfile% - %Windir% - Program files - Root folder ``` The tool also allows the attacker to declare a mutex in order to prevent similar copies to be active on the system. The malware creates several registry and system modifications that reference the mutex which allows Responders to easily detect the entries and delete them from the system in order to start mitigating the infection. The traces are: ``` %AppData%\Microsoft\Windows\mutex-name.cfg %AppData%\Microsoft\Windows\mutex-name.xtr %AppData%\Microsoft\Windows\mutex-name.dat HKCU\Software\mutex-name\InstalledServer HKCU\Software\(mutex-name\ServerStarted ```

Capabilities

XtremeRAT offers a wide selection of features that might leave an easily detectable footprint in the system. These include: - Interactive remote shell. - List installed programs - Registry editor - Process manager, connection monitor, registry editor and file manager. - Download/Execution of files and scripts. - Remote camera monitoring. - Proxy. - USB spreader. - Self deletion after infection. - Remote mic monitoring. - Keylogger. - Open chat. - Install, uninstall, update, restart, disconnect, rename server on demand. - Password stealer

Host Indicators

Systems infected with XtremeRAT have several traces of host based indicators. These are: - The tool performs injection in the following processes: ``` calc.exe notepad.exe explorer.exe svchost.exe firefox.exe iexplorer.exe chrome.exe ``` - Several persistence mechanisms that involve the following registry modifications: ``` HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Active Setup\Installed Components\{randomgen value}\StubPath HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce\ HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce\ HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Windows\Load HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Windows\Load HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Winlogon\Shell HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Winlogon\Shell HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\policies\Explorer\Run HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Policies\Explorer\Run HKCU\Software\"mutex-name"\InstalledServer ``` - Artifact files that might indicate screenshot activity are stored on the following paths ``` %WinDir%\name-of-folder\Mousecap %TEMP%\name-of-folder\Mousecap %AppData%\name-of-folder\Mousecap %UserProfile%\name-of-folder\Mousecap %AllUsersProfile%\name-of-folder\Mousecap %Windir%\name-of-folder\Mousecap Program files\name-of-folder\Mousecap ``` - A copy of the binary is saved in the under the following path: ``` %WinDir%\name-of-folder\ %TEMP%\name-of-folder\ %AppData%\name-of-folder\ %UserProfile%\name-of-folder\ %AllUsersProfile%\name-of-folder\ %Windir%\name-of-folder\ Program files\name-of-folder\ ``` - Standalone infector file that performs consistent connections to the command and control server. Using tools like tcpview can easily detect suspicious connections. The location of the infector file is determined by where the victim downloaded the file to. Therefore its location varies. - Processes running XtremeRAT tend to be standalone if no injection is enabled. It also has the capability to inject itself into several known processes like `explorer.exe, calc.exe, notepad.exe and well known browsers such as firefox, internet explorer and chrome`. One of the tell signs is the running of the process without being open. A tool like process explorer can assist in identifying the malicious process.
